#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:3
msgid "Rust specific roles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:5
msgid ""
"The extension provides the following docutils roles, which can be referenced "
"as ``{<role_name>}`<target>``` in Markdown and as ``:<role_name>:`target``` "
"in reStructuredText."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:8
msgid ""
"For all roles, the target is the double colon (``::``) delimited full Rust "
"path to the item, similar to the path used when importing the item. This "
"syntax is slightly extended to accommodate linking to trait impl blocks and "
"fields within a struct."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:12
msgid ""
"For all importable items like structs, enums, traits, etc., the target path "
"is the Rust import path, either ``<crate_name>::<module_path>::<item>`` or "
"``<executable_name>::<module_path>::<item>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:15
msgid ""
"To link to an implementation of a trait by a struct or enum, the target is "
"provided as ``<crate_name>::<module_path>::<item>::<trait_name>::"
"<trait_item>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:20
msgid ""
"Adding a ``~`` before the path will display only the final portion of the "
"path as the link text. So, ``:rust:fn:`~crate::module::func``` will display "
"only ``func`` as the link text."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:24
msgid "Role targets within docstrings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:26
msgid ""
"When writing docstrings, targets can be specified relative to the module and "
"its imports."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:28
msgid ""
"Any items defined or imported in the same file with a ``use`` statement may "
"be referenced directly. So, ``:rust:struct:`Foo``` will link to a ``struct "
"Foo`` defined or imported within that file. This makes the references within "
"the docstrings much shorter and the docstrings easier to read. The text for "
"the link will be ``Foo`` in this case, without the need for a preceding "
"``~``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:33
msgid ""
"The short reference can also be used for items that are members of or "
"associated with an defined or imported item. For example, a variant of an "
"enum defined within the file can be referenced as ``:rust:struct:`<enum>::"
"<variant>``` within the file itself. In this case, the link text will be "
"``<enum>::<variant>``. A ``~`` can be added here to display only "
"``<variant>`` as the link text."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:38
msgid ""
"Short references are not supported for items that are imported as part of a "
"glob (``*``) import."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:41
msgid "Markdown docstrings and intra-doc links"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:43
msgid ""
"The tool supports rustdoc's :ref:`intra-doc` and targets may be referenced "
"in the markdown docstrings directly using ``[<target>]`` or "
"``[`<target>`]``. This feature also works in docs besides docstrings, but "
"the target must be an absolute path. Literal text enclosed within brackets "
"must be escaped using backslash (e.g. ``\\[not a link]``) otherwise it will "
"appear as a broken link."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:49
msgid "reStructuredText and intra-doc links"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:51
msgid ""
"Behaviour similar to Markdown :ref:`intra-doc` links can be enabled by "
"adding the :rst:role:`rust:any` as the ``default_role`` in Sphinx's ``conf."
"py``. With this, items can be linked simply with ```<target>``` even outside "
"the docstrings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:56
msgid "Provided roles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:60
msgid ""
"``:rust:any:`<target>``` finds any item that matches the target and links to "
"it. This is similar to Sphinx's any_ role, but within the Rust domain. Use "
"this role as the default role for the build to reference Rust items without "
"any role specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:66
msgid ""
"``:rust:crate:`<crate_name>``` links to the crate's documentation, within "
"``lib.rs``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:70
msgid ""
"``:rust:enum:`<enum_path>``` links to an enum's documentation. Specific "
"variant's within the enum can be referenced"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:71
msgid "using the ``struct`` role."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:75
msgid ""
"``:rust:exe:`<executable_name>``` links to an executable's documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:79
msgid "Alias for :rst:role:`rust:exe`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:83
msgid "``:rust:fn:`<fn_path>``` links to a function's documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:85
msgid ""
"To a reference an associated function, use the full path to the impl block "
"where the function is defined, followed by the function's name. See the :rst:"
"role:`rust:impl` documentation below for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:88
msgid ""
"Note that the path ``<trait_path>::<fn>`` references the function "
"declaration within the trait, whereas ``<struct_path>::<trait>::<fn>`` "
"references the implementation of the trait's function for the struct."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:93
msgid "Alias for :rst:role:`rust:fn`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:97
msgid ""
"``:rust:impl:`<impl_path>``` links to an impl block, either of the struct, "
"or for a trait for a struct. The ``<impl_path>`` is provided as "
"``<crate_name>::<module_name>::<item>`` for struct or enum impl blocks and "
"as ``<crate_name>::<module_name>::<item>::<trait_name>`` for trait impl "
"blocks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:101
msgid ""
"When referencing an impl block for a struct or an enum, use the full path to "
"the impl block within the crate. So, if the ``impl Foo`` block is in a "
"different module from the struct itself, the path must reference the module "
"of the impl block. Items within the impl block like functions and variables "
"are then nested under this path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:105
msgid ""
"When referencing a trait impl block, the last two components of the path are "
"``<item>::<trait>``. So, a block ``impl Display for Foo`` is referenced as "
"``crate::module::Foo::Display``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:110
msgid "``:rust:macro:`<macro_path>``` inks to a macro's documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:114
msgid ""
"``:rust:module:`<module_path>``` inks to the module's documentation. The "
"module path here is the Rust path of the"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:115
msgid ""
"module, not its file's path. So, even if the module is defined in a ``mod."
"rs`` file, the path here will be the path to import the module in a ``use`` "
"statement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:120
msgid ""
"``:rust:struct:`<struct_path>``` links to a struct or an enum variant's "
"documentation. For an enum variant, use ``:rust:struct:`<enum_path>::"
"<variant>``` as the target."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:123
msgid ""
"Specific fields within the struct or variant can be referenced using the :"
"rst:role:`rust:variable` role."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:127
msgid ""
"``:rust:trait:`<trait_path>``` links to a trait's documentation. Items "
"defined within the trait are nested under the trait's path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:132
msgid "``:rust:type:`<type_path>``` links to a type's documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:136
msgid ""
"``:rust:variable:`<variable_path>``` links to a static or const variable, or "
"to a field within a struct or enum variant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:139
msgid "For fields of a struct, the path is ``<struct_path>::<field_name>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:140
msgid ""
"For tuple structs, the field's index should be used instead of the name "
"(``<struct_path>::0``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:142
msgid ""
"For an enum variant's fields, the path is ``<enum_path>::<variant>::"
"<field_name>``, with field index instead of name for tuple variants."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/roles.rst:146
msgid "Alias for :rst:role:`rust:variable`."
msgstr ""
